00:45:35,868 --> 00:45:37,128
If you have any questions, fire away.

710
00:45:42,641 --> 00:45:49,927
Hi, that was a great talk, thank you. I'm an Eve player and I've been a big fan of your volunteer groups.

711
00:45:51,008 --> 00:45:55,773
One of my questions though is, have you ever had any problems with the...

712
00:45:58,155 --> 00:46:05,340
a legal gray area of having volunteers who are doing things that are almost like work that you would normally pay them for,

713
00:46:05,440 --> 00:46:11,925
and you're paying them non-monetarily. Does that cause problems for you, and does that change your approach with them?

714
00:46:12,666 --> 00:46:19,391
Are you unable to give them direction in what they're doing, or do they have to just come up with whatever they want to do themselves?

715
00:46:20,091 --> 00:46:25,596
I know there was a lot of discussion about this like a few years ago, but one of the things we do,

716
00:46:26,017 --> 00:46:28,439
we don't mandate like any number of hours from people.

717
00:46:28,459 --> 00:46:33,324
We just want people to be active over time, but we don't mandate, for example,

718
00:46:33,364 --> 00:46:38,268
you have to do this much necessarily to be allowed to be in the program.

719
00:46:38,288 --> 00:46:42,152
We just, you know, you put in the time you can and just stay active and you're all good.

720
00:46:42,212 --> 00:46:43,433
And that's one of the things we do.

721
00:46:44,214 --> 00:46:45,115
Obviously, we just like...

722
00:46:45,935 --> 00:46:47,595
We can't give every task to players.

723
00:46:47,615 --> 00:46:49,095
I mean, there has to be some limit to that.

724
00:46:50,376 --> 00:46:51,676
And people get into it.

725
00:46:51,716 --> 00:46:52,296
They're adults.

726
00:46:52,336 --> 00:46:53,016
They know what they're doing.

727
00:46:53,556 --> 00:46:57,357
There's a very clear line of what this is and what everybody taking part in it.

728
00:46:57,597 --> 00:46:58,517
We've been good with that.

729
00:47:01,278 --> 00:47:06,238
Can you describe any positive or negative experiences with user-created content?

730
00:47:07,459 --> 00:47:11,919
Positive and negative experiences with user-created content.

731
00:47:13,539 --> 00:47:14,640
Well, there's...

732
00:47:15,760 --> 00:47:19,301
I mean, obviously, there's always a lot of drama around some things.

733
00:47:19,361 --> 00:47:22,823
Some people make content to cause drama.

734
00:47:23,303 --> 00:47:25,144
We generally just stay out of that.

735
00:47:25,464 --> 00:47:31,126
We don't get involved, and we try not to touch things that are likely to cause drama in any official way.

736
00:47:31,166 --> 00:47:35,348
So if, for example, someone is a bit of a troll and is making content,

737
00:47:35,368 --> 00:47:37,789
we probably wouldn't commission them for doing work for us.

738
00:47:37,849 --> 00:47:39,369
We deal with people who...

739
00:47:40,137 --> 00:47:43,880
who we trust to understand the bigger picture and do the right thing.

740
00:47:44,200 --> 00:47:47,602
So, yeah, there have been some things, but nothing too terrible.

741
00:47:47,963 --> 00:47:50,344
And we just take care not to, you know, when we're linking to stuff,

742
00:47:50,424 --> 00:47:52,366
to make sure it's OK, it's not something horrible.

743
00:47:54,687 --> 00:47:54,847
Hey.

744
00:47:55,528 --> 00:47:58,530
Hey. So, I'm an absolute disaster when talking to the community.

745
00:47:59,511 --> 00:48:01,412
And I guess with having so many of you developers

746
00:48:02,192 --> 00:48:03,894
directly interfacing with the community,

747
00:48:03,954 --> 00:48:05,415
which is something that they don't do primarily,

748
00:48:05,975 --> 00:48:06,916
is there a...

749
00:48:08,205 --> 00:48:15,708
A single piece of advice or training materials, or how do you prepare those developers to talk and interact with the community?

750
00:48:33,673 --> 00:48:40,847
But one of the things we have in our guidelines, for example, is that we train people not to talk too much about other people's work.

751
00:48:41,208 --> 00:48:44,194
I mean, we as communication professionals, we talk about other people's works.

752
00:48:44,836 --> 00:48:52,918
But someone who's maybe a programmer, he's not talking about something that an artist is doing and vice versa in any detail or promising anything that they can't deliver on.

753
00:48:52,938 --> 00:48:57,338
So we want people to focus on their specialty and rather summon someone else if they need to.

754
00:48:57,378 --> 00:49:00,759
And then we have some guidelines on just being very professional and friendly and all that.

755
00:49:00,819 --> 00:49:05,080
And even if you're doing this, like if you're just chatting to people about your favorite football team or whatever,

756
00:49:05,100 --> 00:49:09,341
just always remember you are an employee first and foremost anytime you're talking to a player.

757
00:49:09,381 --> 00:49:12,722
It's just something that's a common sense thing that people need to...

758
00:49:13,122 --> 00:49:15,824
It needs some training sometimes, but most people can handle it pretty well.

759
00:49:15,844 --> 00:49:17,726
And I think if you allow people to do it, they get better at it.

760
00:49:19,787 --> 00:49:22,029
Hello. Thank you for the talk. Great talk.

761
00:49:22,810 --> 00:49:27,233
I've got two questions, and maybe the answer is worth a separate presentation.

762
00:49:27,914 --> 00:49:28,735
Yeah.

763
00:49:28,855 --> 00:49:35,300
But first of all, we all know that when we're talking about games that have been around for quite a while,

764
00:49:36,681 --> 00:49:41,326
Players there, the players know the game much better than developers.

765
00:49:41,967 --> 00:49:42,167
Yeah.

766
00:49:42,627 --> 00:49:47,752
And how do you approach features that community proposes?

767
00:49:48,353 --> 00:49:49,594
That's the question number one.

768
00:49:49,634 --> 00:49:54,619
Do you have any kind of guidelines to how you like pass stuff to developers or something like that?

769
00:49:55,340 --> 00:49:56,201
And the second one...

770
00:49:57,462 --> 00:50:01,487
Even if you think that the feature the player proposes is good enough,

771
00:50:02,128 --> 00:50:06,493
but there are definitely way more stuff the community brings to you than you can develop.

772
00:50:07,034 --> 00:50:12,560
And even if you agree that this is good, how do you deal with that, like, whining and stuff that,

773
00:50:12,741 --> 00:50:16,005
hey, you're not doing this, I told you to do this, like, years ago?

774
00:50:16,897 --> 00:50:25,207
So community proposing features and how we deal with the, I guess, expectation management of what these features we don't decide to develop.

775
00:50:26,268 --> 00:50:32,696
Well, one thing, for example, that the Council of Stellar Management can do is that they can provide features officially with access to our internal site.

776
00:50:32,716 --> 00:50:33,857
So they make like a feature cart.

777
00:50:34,618 --> 00:50:37,722
for a feature proposal and they propose like roadmap changes and stuff like that.

778
00:50:37,742 --> 00:50:38,743
So that's one formal way.

779
00:50:39,123 --> 00:50:42,146
Then we have, you know, the regular like forums where people propose ideas and

780
00:50:42,587 --> 00:50:45,129
and this active conversation that we have with players

781
00:50:45,930 --> 00:50:48,373
so that like developers that are specialists in an area,

782
00:50:48,393 --> 00:50:51,076
they often have like a group of people that are very good in that area

783
00:50:51,096 --> 00:50:52,257
and they talk to them regularly.

784
00:50:52,297 --> 00:50:54,299
It's like sort of like an unofficially also.

785
00:50:54,659 --> 00:50:56,541
So they get feedback and bounce ideas off people.

786
00:50:57,905 --> 00:51:00,065
So we validate ideas like that.

787
00:51:00,365 --> 00:51:02,926
And then when it comes to deciding what not to do,

788
00:51:02,966 --> 00:51:05,807
I mean, that's classic expectation management.

789
00:51:05,827 --> 00:51:07,907
We have to, you know, there's sometimes

790
00:51:07,947 --> 00:51:09,347
like a lot of noise about something

791
00:51:09,387 --> 00:51:11,648
that we can't realistically get into right now,

792
00:51:11,788 --> 00:51:13,548
or it's just maybe not a great idea.

793
00:51:13,588 --> 00:51:15,989
And then we have to discuss it, spend some time discussing it.

794
00:51:16,409 --> 00:51:19,530
Or, you know, at least if it's a good idea that we have to do,

795
00:51:19,570 --> 00:51:21,510
but we can't do it now, we have to tell them to.

796
00:51:21,670 --> 00:51:24,891
You know, we have to like lay down some information on when

797
00:51:24,911 --> 00:51:25,931
we can do it or something like that.

798
00:51:26,791 --> 00:51:27,052
Thank you.

